  "text": "the stimulus, but most spikes of the synchronized cells would not, because they are distributed around the trigger spikes, as shown by central peaks in cross-correlograms of CM cell pairs [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ) ( Figure S1B ). Therefore, on average, the synchronized spikes would have the same net firing times relative to the spinal stimuli as the trigger spikes and most would arrive after the stimulus. The decrease in the synchrony component therefore confirms the consequent reduction of synaptic efficacy of the synchronized cell(s). The decrease in SpREs when the postsynaptic cells are activated before arrival of the presynaptic input is consistent with a bidirectional STDP rule for excitatory synapses [CITATION_3] .",
